      {
        "id": 2884039,
        "name": "William Kelley",
        "username": "William_Kelley",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/william_kelley/{size}/2314_2.png",
        "created_at": "2020-05-06T09:29:29.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>I have tasted a few 2019s, including my own Chambolle-Musigny, and my very early and informal impressions (which I wouldn\u2019t yet put in print - this is very provisional stuff) is that 2019 is quite a surprising vintage: weather conditions were if anything more extreme than 2018, yet the wines are livelier and more elegant. There is an energy in what I have tasted that\u2019s quite exciting (and this would also appear to apply to the Beaujolais). So I think any notion that it\u2019s 2018-mark two looks to be mistaken. I\u2019m certainly looking forward to tasting the wines systematically later this year.</p>",
        "post_number": 6,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 12,
        "updated_at": "2022-06-03T18:40:21.319Z",
